Bear Hole Reservoir old dam cement landing
Bear Hole Reservoir old dam cement landing.  Dam washed out in August 1955 during a flood.
Glen of the historic Bear Hole restaurant
Glen of the historic Bear Hole restaurant circa mid 1800s to around 1906.
Bear Hole trail leading to the water's edge
Trail leading to the glen and waterfall
Bear Hole Reservoir trail leading to the glen and waterfall of the historic restaurant
Bear Hole Chumba Wumba Trail.  Distance 1.05 miles.  Multi use trail - passive recreation.
Trail leading to section #3 of the M&M Trail
Poorly maintained trail leading to section 3 of the M&M Trail.  Easy to miss via the Chumba Wumba.
Metacomet Monadnock Trail Section 3.  Also known as the New England National Scenic Trail.
Bear Hole - Quarry Trail.  Trail leads to the Lane Quarry and trailhead for section 3 of the M&M Trail.  Steep, uneven terrain.

M&M Trail section 3 in Bear Hole.  Also known as the New England National Scenic Trail.  Will lead you towards the reservoir's dam.  It's a woodland trail.  You can sign your name and leave a comment in a sign-in log book along the way.
Bear Hole Inferno Trail.  Easy woodland terrain.
Bear Hole Rd / Great Plains Rd at Morgan Rd.
Cement jersey barriers and small parking area
Inferno Trail.  Easy woodland terrain.  Distance approximately 1/2 mile.  Service gate recessed from the road is the trailhead.
Bear Hole Reservoir Watershed - Prospect Avenue gated section.  Distance from Four Corners to the Old Holyoke Rd gate is 1.13 miles.  Easy terrain.  Road is mostly pavement millings.
Trail leading up to East Mountain.  Must cross Paucatuck Brook and the Pioneer Valley Railroad Track to get onto the mountain.
Trail leading to / from Millville.  Easy terrain.  Follows the water's edge.

Road closed to thru traffic.  Mostly pavement millings on road surface. Mud puddles towards the road's end, which is a hairpin curve at the RR track and near Ashley Reservoir in Holyoke. Millville distance .98 miles
Lost Pond - Bear Hole Reservoir Watershed
Brook crossing on hiking trail.  No bridge.  Difficult to cross unless water flow is low.  In Spring it is impassable without getting wet.
Millville - hairpin curve.  End of Millville
Millville Road - hairpin curve.  End of the road.  Continue to onto abutting trail for more recreation.
Unnamed trailhead leading to Cauldron Trail and up to East Mountain.  Mixed terrain.  Some uneven rocky terrain.
Trail leading up to East Mountain ridge
Trail leading to a trail below the East Mountain Ridge and to section 4 of the M&M Trail.  Steep, uneven, mountain terrain.
Cauldron Trail - mostly uneven rocky mountain terrain.  Steep sections.  Mountain woodlands.  Will lead you towards Holyoke.
Dead end trail to beaver pond.
Adrenaline Trail - mostly even ground, some slightly rocky and mild hills.
Trail leading towards Ashley Reservoir in Holyoke.  Mostly easy terrain.
Trail leading to / from East Mountain.  Steep, uneven mountain terrain section.  Some swampy areas.  Some easy terrain.
Flooded section of trail.  Beaver Dam.  Unless crossing the narrow dam or wading through knee to waste deep water, it's impassable.  Water to one side.  Thick swamp to the other side.
Mix of paved and pavement millings surface.  Easy terrain.  Woodlands and wetland zones.  Distance 1.13 miles to the Old Holyoke Gate.
Site of homestead ruins.  Cement structure and stone cellar.
Bridge over the Pioneer Valley Railroad Track.  Closed to traffic.  Can support foot traffic, but use caution.
Trail junction.  Follow straight for M&M section 3 in either direction. Follow the short trail and you'll be heading to / from the reservoir area.
Hiking trail that follows route of defunct power line right-of-way.  Mostly overgrown, but passable.  Lots of wildlife sightings possible.  Hawk, turkey, deer.  Mixed terrain.
Pumping station access road yellow gate
DPW access road to Bear Hole pumping station.  Open to passive recreation.  Level, easy terrain.  Mostly pavement millings surface.
Reservoir perimeter road trail.  Level, dirt surface.  Easy terrain.  Will lead you to the glen of the restaurant. .65 miles to the glen of the restaurant
Trail leading to / from service road
Trail leading to / from pumping station service road.  Easy terrain. .30 miles
Hemlock ridge trail.  Easy terrain.  Trail follows above Paucatuck Brook.  Nice views of the brook.
Stay to the left at the trail junction and you'll continue above the ridge of Paucatuck Brook.  Trail loops back out to Bear Hole Road / Great Plains.  Also a large beaver pond to visit.
Beaver pond.  Informal trail leading to it from the Hemlock Trail.
Hemlock Ridge extension trail.  Easy terrain trail through pine tree and hemlock forest.
Inferno Trail.  Easy terrain.  Trailhead has service gate recessed from the road.  1/2 mile circuit
Hiking trail flooded with deep beaver pond.  Not passable.
